article.description: Forward Tamika Whitmore scored a playoff career-high 24 points, leading the New York Liberty past the Indiana Fever 84-65 to stay alive in the best-of-three Eastern Conference semifinals.
article.headline: Whitmore delivers as Liberty pull even
article.linkText: Staying alive: Liberty rip Fever to tie series
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Tamika Whitmore made sure the New York Liberty
didn't suffer another embarrassing loss.

	   Whitmore scored a playoff career-high 24 points as the Liberty
defeated the Indiana Fever 84-65 Sunday, forcing a decisive Game 3
in the Eastern Conference semifinals.

	   The winner of the game Tuesday at Madison Square Garden faces
the Washington Mystics, which swept the Charlotte Sting on
Saturday.

	   New York's victory came after losing 73-55 in Game 1, the
Liberty's worst playoff loss.

	   "We really made a statement,'' Whitmore said. "We just have to
build on it.''

	   The Liberty has made it past the first round in each of their
previous four playoff appearances and relied on Whitmore's
10-for-12 shooting, trademark defense and blistering 59-percent
shooting in the victory.

	   They also kept rookie of the year Tamika Catchings in check.
Catchings finished with 20 points and 14 rebounds, but made just
two baskets after halftime.

	   "I probably stepped out of the offense too many times,''
Catchings said. "In the first half, I made a consistent effort to
stay in the offense and try to get my shot off. With a veteran
team, with such great players, if you don't attack right when they
start attacking you, you'll get down and keep going down.''

	   Crystal Robinson and Johnson double-teamed Catchings and limited
her shooting in the second half.

	   ''(Catchings) is a phenomenal talent,'' New York coach Richie
Adubato said. "But we have two people who have a lot a pride. We
mixed up our defense as much as possible to try to contain her.''

	   New York led by as many as 24 points in the second half. Tari
Phillips scored 20 points, reserve Becky Hammon had 13 and Vickie
Johnson added 10 for the Liberty, who shot 5-for-10 from 3-point
range.

	   Hammon's driving layups and 3-pointer helped the Liberty to an
11-point lead in the first half.

	   "My job is to get this team going,'' said Hammon, who finished
5-for-8 from the field. "I got some easy looks in the first
half.''

	   The third-year Fever shot 36.1 percent from the field. Indiana,
0-5 at the Garden, had won seven of its last eight games.

	   "They took it to us,'' Indiana coach Nell Fortner said. "We
didn't have an answer for them.

	   The top-seeded Liberty outscored the Fever 50-28 in the paint.

	   New York took a 38-31 halftime lead after shooting 57 percent,
including 5-for-7 from 3-point range.

	   Catchings, meanwhile, could not keep the Fever in the game.
Though she finished second in the WNBA in scoring (18.6), fourth in
rebounds (8.6), and is the first rookie to lead the league in
steals (2.94), she disappeared in the second half.

	   "Tamika has been a terrific player for us all year long, but it
has been a total team effort,'' Fortner said. "We just need to be
a complete team Tuesday night.''
